Exercise 1: Comparing HLY in Terms of Life Expectancy
cor(avg.life.expectancy,HLY) 
## [1] 0.8749937
plot(avg.life.expectancy,HLY, xlab= "Inequality-Adjusted Life Expectancy", ylab= "Happy Life Years", main = "Life Expectancy Affecting Number of Happy Years in Life")


lm(HLY~avg.life.expectancy)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = HLY ~ avg.life.expectancy)
## 
## Coefficients:
##         (Intercept)  avg.life.expectancy  
##             -63.734                1.325
abline(-63.734, 1.325, col="red")

The correlation between the two variables presented above display a strong positive relationship. The equation of the regression line, y=-63.734+1.325x, can be used to measure the differences of the actual value to predicted value of the countrys happy life years in terms of inequality adjusted life expectancy.

cor(avg.life.expectancy,HLY)^2
## [1] 0.765614

The regression line acurrately represents the positive relationship between the variables because the coefficient of determination of the model above is 0.766, which is close to 1.

-63.734+1.325*83.2
## [1] 46.506

Comparing the residuals for the United States and a country of my choice, Japan, the residual for Japans life expectancy to happy life years is -2.506. The actual number of happy life years is measured to be below the regression line by a small amount.

-63.734+1.325*78.8
## [1] 40.676

The residual for the United States life expectancy to happy life years is 6.124. The actual number of happy life years is measured to be above the regression line by a moderate amount

Exercise 2: Comparing Ecological Footprint in Terms of GDP per Capita
cor(GDP.per.capita,footprint)
## [1] 0.7963459
plot(GDP.per.capita,footprint, xlab="GDP Per Capita", main="Economic Activity Affecting Ecological Footprint Across All Countries", ylab ="Ecological Footprint (gha/capita)")

lm(footprint~GDP.per.capita)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = footprint ~ GDP.per.capita)
## 
## Coefficients:
##    (Intercept)  GDP.per.capita  
##      1.968e+00       9.288e-05
abline(1.968, 9.288e-05, col="red")

The GDP per capita to ecological footprint displays a strong positive relationship. This can be represented with the equation y=1.968+9.288e-05x.

cor(GDP.per.capita,footprint)^2
## [1] 0.6341668

In otherwords, \(\hat{y}=1.968+9.288e-05x\) is a regression line that best fits the data points above because the coefficient of determination of a model is 0.634. I would consider R^2 to be a weaker representation if it calculates to below 0.5, while our data does not.

1.968+9.288e-05*46679
## [1] 6.303546

Comparing the residuals for the United States and a country of my choice, Japan, the actual to predicted value for Japans economic activity per person to ecological footprint, the residual is -1.304. The actual number of happy life years is measured to be below the regression line by a small amount. In this example, it is better for the residual to be negative of the regression line. This number shows that there are more people in Japan with less of an ecological footprint.

1.968+9.288e-05*51457
## [1] 6.747326

The residual for the United States life expectancy to happy life years is 1.453. The actual number of happy life years is measured to be above the regression line by a small amount.

Exercise 3: Asia Pacific Region
asia.only <-subset(spring_2020_lab_2_data,region== "Asia Pacific")

cor(asia.only$GDP.per.capita,asia.only$footprint)
## [1] 0.8534438
lm(asia.only$footprint~asia.only$GDP.per.capita)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = asia.only$footprint ~ asia.only$GDP.per.capita)
## 
## Coefficients:
##              (Intercept)  asia.only$GDP.per.capita  
##                1.6756987                 0.0001177
plot(asia.only$GDP.per.capita,asia.only$footprint, ylab ="Ecological Footprint (gha/capita)", xlab = "GDP Per Capita", main = "Economic Activity Affecting Ecological Footprint Across All Countries")

abline(1.6756987,0.0001177, col="red")

cor(asia.only$GDP.per.capita,asia.only$footprint)^2
## [1] 0.7283663

The worldwide pattern compared to the Asia Pacific region pattern are similar because both graphs present a strong positive relationship. However, the correlation between countries in the Asia Pacific region show a correlation of 0.853 because the trend line is steeper than the pattern presented in the worldwide data. To show that the regression line is the best representation for the plots we determine R^2, which calculates to 0.728, showing a strong fit.

Exercise 4: Summary

I observed in my findings that when measuring GDP per capita to ecological footprint, both the worldwide data and the Asia Pacific region data presented a positive relationship. Moreover, the relationship showed consistency because the countries were spread out across the x-axis relatively close to the regression line, and there werent certain intervals along the x-axis where no points appeared. I found some of the outliers to be interesting from this observation. Luxembourg has a GDP of 105,447 and 15.8 (gha per capita) for ecological footprint. This is one of the countries with the highest GDP to ecological footprint, while the population of Luxemburg is only 530,946, which is smaller than the majority of the countries worldwide. Moving forward, Id like to do more research on the country of Luxemburg to give more context as to why it has such a great residual.
